  "doc_id": "33569",
  "text": "Following publication of the structure of dimeric CK2β, Meggio et al. [CITATION_1] demonstrated that recombinant CK2β treated with sulphydryl-modifying reagents fails to form homodimers, but forms αβ dimers, and α # β\\αβ # trimers, in itro. Since CK2β exerts both positive and negative regulatory effects on CK2 activity [20,30,32a] and because one CK2β subunit appears to interact with both catalytic subunits within the CK2 tetramer [CITATION_2] , we postulated that αβ dimers, which are unable to form tetrameric complexes, may exhibit dysregulated CK2 activity. To test this prediction, we constructed a Myc-tagged CK2β mutant in which two of the conserved zinc-finger residues, Cys\"!* and Cys\"\"%, were mutated to serine. Our objectives were to study the effects of disrupting the zinc finger of CK2β on the formation of multi-subunit CK2 complexes, and to evaluate the usefulness of such a mutant as a dominant unregulated mutant of CK2. Results from this study indicate that the zinc finger mutant is neither able to form homodimers nor able to interact with the catalytic subunits of CK2 either in itro or in cells. Furthermore, we demonstrate that the mutant is not appreciably phosphorylated in cells and is rapidly degraded. Importantly, these results are in good accordance with a model whereby complexes between CK2β subunits precede the formation of tetrameric CK2 complexes, and whereby formation of CK2β homodimers is required for the incorporation of catalytic subunits into tetrameric CK2 complexes.",
